data.chText: 愤慨的；愤怒的；义愤的
data.enText: feeling or showing anger and surprise because you think that you have been treated unfairly

data.chText: 愤慨的信 / 神情
data.enText: an indignant letter/look

data.chText: 她对于自己受到的待遇大为光火。
data.enText: She was very indignant at the way she had been treated.

data.chText: 他们因没有受到邀请而愤愤不平。
data.enText: They were indignant that they hadn't been invited.

data.chText: “我当然不是在问他！”她愤然反驳说。
data.enText: ‘I'm certainly not asking him!’ she retorted indignantly.

data.chText: 以上各词均形容人愤怒和 / 或发怒。
data.enText: All these words describe people feeling and/or showing anger.
angry

data.chText: 指愤怒、发怒：
data.enText: feeling or showing anger

data.chText: 请别生我的气。
data.enText: Please don't be angry with me.

data.chText: 广场上聚满了成千上万的愤怒示威者。
data.enText: Thousands of angry demonstrators filled the square.
mad

data.chText: 指愤怒或发怒：
data.enText: [not before noun] ( informal , especially NAmE ) angry

data.chText: 他大动肝火，愤然离去。
data.enText: He got mad and walked out.

data.chText: 我迟到了，她非常生气。
data.enText: She's mad at me for being late.

data.chText: 在非正式的美国英语中，mad为表示愤怒或发怒（angry）的常用词；在英国英语中，尤其是在短语go mad中，mad可表示非常气愤：
data.enText: Mad is the usual word for ‘angry’ in informal American English. When used in British English, especially in the phrase go mad , it can mean ‘very angry’.

data.chText: 父亲看到你的所作所为会非常气愤。
data.enText: Dad'll go mad when he sees what you've done.

data.chText: go mad也可指发疯、发狂或激动起来。
data.enText: ‘Go mad’ can also mean ‘go crazy’ or ‘get very excited’.
indignant

data.chText: 指因遭遇或见到不公平的事而愤慨、愤怒：
data.enText: feeling or showing anger and surprise because you think that you or sb else has been treated unfairly

data.chText: 她对自己受到的待遇大为光火。
data.enText: She was very indignant at the way she had been treated.
cross

data.chText: 指十分愤怒、恼怒：
data.enText: ( rather informal , especially BrE ) rather angry or annoyed

data.chText: 我因他迟到而十分生气。
data.enText: I was quite cross with him for being late.

data.chText: 该词常为儿童用语或对儿童的用语。
data.enText: This word is often used by or to children.
irate

data.chText: 指极其愤怒的、暴怒的：
data.enText: very angry

data.chText: 愤怒的顾客
data.enText: irate customers

data.chText: 言辞激愤的信
data.enText: an irate letter

data.chText: irate后通常不跟介词：
data.enText: Irate is not usually followed by a preposition.
She was irate with me/about it.
to look/sound/seem angry/mad/indignant/cross
They were angry/indignant/cross that they hadn't been invited.
It really makes me angry/mad/cross.
to get angry/mad/cross
to be angry/mad/indignant/cross about/at sth
angry/cross with sb (for doing sth)

simple_means.memory_skill: in 不 + dign 值得，有价值的；高贵的 + ant …的 → 愤慨的，愤怒的

tr: angered at something unjust or wrong
example: umbrageous at the loss of their territory

value.def: If you are indignant, you are shocked and angry, because you think that something is unjust or unfair.

example.ex: He is indignant at suggestions that they were secret agents...
example.tran: 有人暗示他们可能是特务,这让他非常气愤。

example.ex: MPs were indignant that the government had not consulted them...
example.tran: 政府没有事先征求他们的意见,下院议员们感到很愤怒。

example.ex: Sheena gave her an indignant look.
example.tran: 希娜愤怒地看了她一眼。

example.ex: 'That is not true,' Erica said indignantly.
example.tran: “那不是真的,”埃丽卡愤怒地说。

rootsaffixes.title: dign

dign 值得，有价值的；高贵的 + ity 具备某种性质，状况 → 尊严；庄严
in 不 + dign 值得，有价值的；高贵的 + ant …的 → 愤慨的，愤怒的
in 不 + dign 值得，有价值的；高贵的 + ation 行为，过程，状态，结果 → 愤怒
in 不 + dign 值得，有价值的；高贵的 + ity 具备某种性质，状况 → 轻视；侮辱
